165–1193","–Female":"Deceased","1165":"1165","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1193":"1193","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Daughter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Dawtrey</b>, see   Daughtry   and also   Daughters  . The surname is most common in Yorkshire and Sussex, where the medieval <i>Dawtrey</i> family held lands in the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Daughters","meanings":["English (London): variant of <b>Dafter</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, apparently from Middle English <i>doughter</i>, <i>dohtor</i>, <i>douter</i> (Old English <i>dohtor</i>) ‘daughter’, often pronounced in early modern English as <i>dafter</i>. For the name to be borne by a man, such that it became a hereditary surname, is surprising, though there are occasional instances of men being named in this way (unless they are clerical errors or it was a surname acquired by the retainers of an heiress of an important family). Alternatively, alternatively <i>Daughter</i>, <i>Daughters</i> might be a simplified pronunciation of <b>Dawtry</b> (see   Daughtery  ), a surname well evidenced in Yorkshire and Sussex, where <i>Doughter</i> and <i>Daughter</i> also occur, in which case the change to <i>Dafter</i> will have arisen through misinterpretation."]},{"name":"Daughtry","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Dawtrey</b>, a habitational name with fused French preposition <i>d(e)</i>, for someone from Hauterive in Orne, France, named from Old French <i>haute rive</i> ‘high bank’ (rendered into Latin <i>Alta Ripa</i>). The medieval <i>Dawtrey</i> family had lands in Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, and Sussex in the 12th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":80,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Ca